Sure — a small CSS block keeps all these palette rules self‑contained.  
Here’s a snippet that can drop into your digital style sheet or print template:

```css
/* Calm Dialogue Workbook – Color & Font Spec */

/* Default Light Mode */
body {
  background-color: #FFFFFF;
  color: #222222;
  font-family: "Source Sans Pro", Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;
  line-height: 1.4;
}

/* Accent colors */
h1, h2, h3 {
  color: #5BA4CF;        /* calm blue headings */
}
table th {
  color: #3B8686;        /* teal accents for tables */
}

/* High-contrast print overrides */
@media print and (color-index: 0) {
  body {
    color: #000000;
    background-color: #FFFFFF;
  }
  h1, h2, h3 {
    color: #000000;
    font-weight: 700;
  }
}

/* Dark Mode (screen) */
@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) {
  body {
    background-color: #121212;
    color: #E6E6E6;
  }
  h1, h2, h3 {
    color: #7CC4EE;
  }
  table th {
    color: #69C3C3;
  }
}

/* Sepia / Eye-strain Reduction */
.theme-sepia {
  background-color: #F6EFE4;
  color: #2E2B25;
}
.theme-sepia h1, .theme-sepia h2, .theme-sepia h3 {
  color: #4C99BF;
}
.theme-sepia table th {
  color: #3F7F7F;
}
```

Place this file in the workbook’s assets folder and reference it in your PDF or web export options so the correct palette loads automatically depending on environment.  

